### 3. `rx()` - Complete Overload Reference

The `rx()` function has **4 overloads** for different rendering patterns.

#### Overload 1: Component with Reactive Props

```tsx
rx(Component, { prop1: signal1, prop2: "static" });
rx("div", { children: count, className: "counter" });
```

**When to use:**

- Mix signal and static props
- Use existing components with signals
- Convenient inline rendering

**How it works:**

- Signal props are automatically tracked
- Static props pass through unchanged
- Component re-renders when signal props change

**Examples:**

```tsx
// Native elements
const count = signal(42);
rx("div", {
  children: count,
  className: "counter",
  style: { color: "blue" },
});

// Custom components
const user = signal({ name: "Alice" });
rx(UserCard, {
  user: user, // Signal prop - reactive
  theme: "dark", // Static prop
  onEdit: handleEdit, // Static callback
});

// Multiple signals
rx(Dashboard, {
  user: userSignal,
  posts: postsSignal,
  settings: settingsSignal,
  loading: false, // Static
});
```

**‚ö†Ô∏è IMPORTANT WARNING:**

‚ùå **NEVER use `rx()` directly in element attributes!**

```tsx
// ‚ùå WRONG - Won't be reactive!
<input value={rx(signal)} />
<div className={rx(theme)} />
```

‚úÖ **CORRECT - Use one of these instead:**

```tsx
// Option 1: Wrap entire element
{
  rx({ signal }, (v) => <input value={v.signal} />);
}

// Option 2: Use component form (Overload 1)
{
  rx("input", { value: signal });
}

// Option 3: Hoist signal outside render
const MyInput = () => rx("input", { value: signal });
```

**Why?** `rx()` returns a component that subscribes. In attributes, it's evaluated once and won't re-subscribe.

**‚ö†Ô∏è PERFORMANCE NOTE: Multiple `rx()` Calls**

If your component contains **many `rx()` calls** (3+), consider using `useWatch()` instead for better performance:

```tsx
// ‚ùå LESS OPTIMAL: Many rx() calls create many subscriptions
function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{rx(title)}</h1>
      <p>{rx(description)}</p>
      <span>{rx(count)}</span>
      <span>{rx(status)}</span>
      <div>{rx(userData, "name")}</div>
      {/* ... many more rx() calls */}
    </div>
  );
}

// ‚úÖ BETTER: Single useWatch subscription
function Dashboard() {
  const [awaited] = useWatch({ title, description, count, status, userData });

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{awaited.title}</h1>
      <p>{awaited.description}</p>
      <span>{awaited.count}</span>
      <span>{awaited.status}</span>
      <div>{awaited.userData.name}</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Why?**

- Each `rx()` creates a separate component with its own subscription
- `useWatch()` creates a single subscription for all signals
- Component re-renders once when any tracked signal changes
- More efficient for components with many reactive values

**When to use `rx()` vs `useWatch()`:**

- Use `rx()`: 1-2 signals, complex rendering logic, or async signals
- Use `useWatch()`: 3+ signals, simple display, or performance-critical components

